Public health institutions were not spared. Health and Human Services Secretary Robert F. Kennedy Jr. dismissed all 17 members of the Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices, the body that advises the CDC on vaccine schedules, and then appointed eight new members, including figures known for spreading vaccine misinformation. He described the purge as a \'93clean sweep\'94 to restore confidence, but the effect was to politicize a core scientific advisory process. At the same time, the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission\'92s acting chair ordered staff to halt processing of gender\uc0\u8209 identity discrimination claims and downgraded them to the lowest priority, while dismissing six ongoing cases and removing the \'93X\'94 gender marker from intake forms. These decisions signaled that statutory protections for transgender and nonbinary people would not be enforced in practice. In both domains, expertise and rights were subordinated to ideological preference.\
