The administration also worked to rewrite national memory in more overt ways. Trump announced a \'93National Garden of American Heroes,\'94 a federally curated pantheon of 250 statues meant to celebrate a particular vision of the nation\'92s past. He issued an order to \'93restore truth and sanity to American history\'94 by reinstating monuments and memorials that had been removed or altered, emphasizing a positive view of heritage. He traveled to Fort Bragg to declare that Army bases would once again bear the names of Confederate generals, defying prior congressional decisions. At the Kennedy Center, he removed the board chair and longtime president, criticizing the institution as \'93too woke\'94 and promising an overhaul; ticket sales and performances suffered. In Florida and elsewhere, book bans and curriculum restrictions narrowed which stories about race, gender, and power could be told in classrooms. The Smithsonian\'92s governing board, in a notable act of resistance, rebuffed Trump\'92s attempt to fire Kim Sajet, director of the National Portrait Gallery, asserting its independence. But the broader pattern was clear. Public history and culture were being curated from above, with dissenting narratives defunded, sidelined, or erased.\
