Amid these pressures, some institutions and actors pushed back. Federal courts in Massachusetts and Washington, D.C., blocked Trump\'92s executive order requiring proof of citizenship to vote in federal elections, ruling that the Constitution does not grant the president authority to unilaterally change voting eligibility. A federal court in Texas halted the use of the Alien Enemies Act for deportations, and another judge ordered the release of Palestinian activist Mahmoud Khalil from detention as a supposed foreign\uc0\u8209 policy threat, though he could still face charges over his green\u8209 card application. The Smithsonian\'92s board defended its governance structure against presidential interference. Local governments, like Glendale, California, terminated contracts to hold ICE detainees, citing community division and state law. Scientists at the National Institutes of Health signed a letter opposing administration policies they said undermined the agency\'92s mission. These acts did not reverse the week\'92s structural shifts, but they showed that the moral floor had not collapsed everywhere.\
